  "prompt": "Where can I find device art generators for Samsung S5?",
  "response": "Finding device art generators *specifically* for the Samsung Galaxy S5 is proving difficult. Most online device art generator tools focus on more modern, widely-used devices. The S5 is quite old now.\n\nHowever, here's a breakdown of why and what you can do:\n\n**Why It's Difficult:**\n\n* **Age of the Device:** The S5 was released in 2014.  Many websites and tools are not maintained with older devices in mind.  Keeping up with the constant stream of new phone models is a lot of work.\n* **Lower Demand:** Fewer developers are targeting the S5 specifically, so there's less need for device art.\n* **Image Size/Resolution:** S5 screen resolutions are significantly lower than modern devices. Most new tools focus on higher resolutions for better-looking marketing materials.\n\n**What You Can Try:**\n\n1. **General Device Art Generators (and Customize):**\n\n   * **Placeit.net:** This is a popular option.  While they may not have a *specific* S5 template, search for \"Android Phone Mockup.\"  You might find something close enough. You can then slightly adjust the image within Placeit to make it resemble the S5 more accurately.\n\n   * **Smartmockups.com:** Similar to Placeit, search for \"Android phone mockup.\"  You'll need to look carefully to see if any even remotely resemble the S5.  Customization options might allow you to tweak the color and shape a bit.\n\n   * **Applaunchpad.io:**  Similar to the above, search broadly for Android device mockups.\n\n2. **DIY (Do It Yourself):**  This is the most reliable (and potentially best looking) option:\n\n   * **Find a High-Quality S5 Image:** Search Google Images for a \"Samsung Galaxy S5 PNG\" (PNG is important because it allows for transparent backgrounds). Look for images that are large and clean.  Avoid images with reflections or strong shadows that will make your screenshot look unnatural.\n\n   * **Use a Photo Editor (Photoshop, GIMP, Photopea):**\n      * **Photoshop (paid):** Industry standard.\n      * **GIMP (free):** Powerful open-source alternative to Photoshop.\n      * **Photopea (free, browser-based):**  A very capable Photoshop clone that runs in your browser.  Highly recommended if you don't have Photoshop or GIMP installed.\n\n   * **Steps:**\n      1. Open the S5 PNG image in your photo editor.\n      2. Find the screen area.  This is usually a clearly defined rectangle.\n      3.  **Create a Clipping Mask (or Use Smart Objects):** This is the key.  You want to insert your screenshot *inside* the screen area of the phone image, so it looks like it's *on* the phone.\n         * **Clipping Mask:** Place your screenshot layer above the S5 image layer (or the screen area of the S5 image).  Right-click on the screenshot layer and choose \"Create Clipping Mask\" (or the equivalent in your photo editor).\n         * **Smart Object (Photoshop):**  Convert the screen area of the S5 image into a Smart Object.  Double-click the Smart Object to open a new tab.  Place your screenshot in this new tab, save it, and it will automatically update in the main S5 image.\n      4. **Adjust Perspective (if necessary):** If the screenshot looks \"flat\" compared to the phone, you might need to use the \"Perspective\" or \"Distort\" tools in your photo editor to slightly adjust the screenshot's perspective to match the phone's angle.\n      5. **Add Subtle Shadows/Reflections (Optional):** To make it look more realistic, you can add very subtle shadows around the edges of the screenshot where it meets the phone bezel.\n\n3. **Search Older Design Resources:**\n\n   * **DeviantArt, Dribbble, Behance:** These are design communities where you might find older PSD templates or device mockups.  Search for \"Samsung Galaxy S5 PSD\" or \"S5 Mockup.\"  Be aware that the quality and license of these resources can vary.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n* **Image Quality:** Start with high-quality screenshots and phone images.  Low-resolution images will look pixelated.\n* **Screen Resolution:** The S5 has a 1920x1080 (Full HD) screen resolution.  Make sure your screenshots are at least that resolution for best results.  If your screenshots are smaller, you can upscale them slightly, but avoid overdoing it, as it can introduce artifacts.\n* **Device Color:**  The S5 came in several colors (black, white, gold, blue). Choose a phone image that matches the color of your app/design or that complements it.\n* **Accuracy:** Pay attention to the details to make it look realistic. The goal is to make it appear like the screenshot is genuinely on the phone.\n\nGood luck!  While a dedicated S5 device art generator is unlikely to be found, the DIY method with a good photo editor and PNG image will give you the best results.\n",
